"{\"uid\": \"semafor.com-article-07-29-2024-olympics-china-glimpse-lgbtq-representation\", \"text\": \"Intelligence for the New World Economy  Insights from Al Jazeera, Bloomberg, Time Magazine, The Washington Post, Nikkei Asia, and Reuters  Sign up for Semafor Flagship:The daily global news briefing you can trust.Read it now.  For a Chinese audience, the Paris Olympics opening ceremony Friday offered a rare glimpse of LGBTQ representation \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 and a chance to air grievances against state media censorship.  Broadcasters for CCTV appeared too stunned to speak during a drag performance and another involving men kissing. Afterward, the topics \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cCCTV is silent\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cdrag queens\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d trended on Chinese social media platform Weibo for a full day alongsidevideo clipsof the live broadcast from Paris.  Some users lamented missing the broadcast, which aired during the night in China, while others praised the Olympics for the display of diversity. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was a beautiful night to stay up for,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d wrote one Weibo user.    After fumbling the broadcast, Chinese social media users mocked CCTV as becoming \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWesternized\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d as a play on the government\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s stance that LGBTQ rights are aWestern ideathat threaten Chinese values. The phrase, however, has been used by Chinese people online to evade censorship and deride the authorities\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 draconian stance. The government has curbed college-run LGBTQ clubs, shut down social media accounts, and waged an online war against \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ceffeminate men,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and essentially excluded LGBTQ people from public life. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cDespite morerestrictions on LGBT+ advocacy in China, the community has shown resilience,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Yuhsuan Chien, a China Dissent Monitor analyst, told Nikkei Aasia earlier this year, noting that government pressure has made online advocacy more common.  Across the strait in Taiwan, same-sex marriage is permitted (China does not allow it), as are Pride parades, LGBTQ films, and drag performances. Earlier this year, former president Tsai Ing-wen eveninvitedan award winning Taiwanese drag queen to perform at the Presidential Office Building. Taiwan\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s progress in LGBTQ rights in the generally conservative East Asia \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094\\u00c2\\u00a0it was the first Asian territory to legalize same-sex marriage in 2019 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094\\u00c2\\u00a0has helped it forge a distinct national identity, anddistinguish itselffrom China, The Washington Post wrote. Support for the LGBTQ community has also become animportant aspectof young Taiwanese people\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s sense of national identity, Nikkei Asia reported.  Sign up for SemaforFlagship  Intelligence for the New World Economy\"}"